  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Congratulatory Letter on the Crown Prince's Birthday
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servants humbly report: We have learned that the Crown Prince, Your Highness, received felicitations from all quarters on the eighth day of this month, his auspicious birthday. Such abundance of good wishes benefits the people, for it comes in the season when the southern wind dispels the grievances of the common folk. And now, behold—a son is born! The heavens themselves mark this occasion with their divine radiance, and auspicious clouds gather thick while songs of joy overflow.

    We respectfully contemplate: The Crown Prince's wisdom surpasses even Yu's heir Qi of old, and his filial devotion exceeds that of King Chang of Zhou. He bears the bright radiance of gold and the generous abundance of jade—such noble bearing! He embodies the surging depths of the ocean and the luminous splendor of mountains—such virtue! Thus do ruler and minister, elder and younger, all probe the wellspring of threefold goodness, and the cessation of litigation and the songs of the people reveal the trust of ten thousand families.

    On this blessed day of your son's arrival, multiplied blessings now descend upon you. Though your servants remain confined within their watch, unable to hasten forward with urgent steps, we greet with joy this star-bright hour of the prince's birth that flows like rainbows through the palace. As the sun and moon hang resplendent in the heavens, we reverently sing your doubled glory.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Crown Prince' (王太子) refers to the heir apparent to the Korean throne during the Joseon period.
  - key: ''
    value: References to Qi (啓), the legendary founder of the Xia dynasty, and King Chang (昌), father of King Wu of Zhou, invoke exemplary rulers from Chinese antiquity as models for the Prince's virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three kinds of goodness' (三善) refers to virtues essential to rulership in Confucian philosophy.
